<paragraph blockId="29.[189,1399,907,1458]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
This species was described based on two male specimens collected by Gordon Floyd Ferris on 
<date pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1919-06-29">June 29, 1919</date>
, at La Paz, 
<collectingCountry box="[442,535,942,968]" name="Mexico" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Mexico</collectingCountry>
. Ferris (
<date box="[635,770,942,969]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1893" valueMax="1958">1893–1958</date>
) was an American entomologist specialist on ‘small insects’, like lice, parasitic flies and small blood-sucking 
<taxonomicName authority="(Usinger 1959)" baseAuthorityName="Usinger" baseAuthorityYear="1959" box="[910,1236,977,1004]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">
Hemiptera (
<bibRefCitation author="Usinger" box="[1055,1227,977,1004]" firstAuthor="Usinger" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="193 - 195" refId="ref22253" refString="Usinger R. L. 1959. Gordon Floyd Ferris 1893 - 1958. The Pan-Pacific Entomologist 35 (1 - 4): 1 - 12. Velarde C. N. 2006. Edmundo Escomel. Acta medica peruana 23: 193 - 195." type="journal article" year="1959">Usinger 1959</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. In 1919, he made an extensive field trip to 
<collectingRegion box="[556,738,1012,1038]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Baja California</collectingRegion>
with the American herpetologist Joseph Richard Slevin (
<date box="[197,334,1047,1074]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1881" valueMax="1957">1881–1957</date>
), where both males studied by 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[697,896,1047,1073]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="49 - 56" refId="ref19992" refString="Cockerell T. D. A. 1924. Anthophorid bees in the collection of the California Academy of Sciences. The Pan-Pacific Entomologist 1: 49 - 56." type="journal article" year="1924">Cockerell (1924)</bibRefCitation>
were collected. In the original description, 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[189,390,1082,1108]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="49 - 56" refId="ref19992" refString="Cockerell T. D. A. 1924. Anthophorid bees in the collection of the California Academy of Sciences. The Pan-Pacific Entomologist 1: 49 - 56." type="journal article" year="1924">Cockerell (1924)</bibRefCitation>
did not indicate which male was the 
<typeStatus box="[841,947,1082,1108]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">holotype</typeStatus>
, and he also failed to indicate the sex of the exemplars, citing that they were two females. 
<bibRefCitation author="Snelling" box="[814,998,1117,1143]" firstAuthor="Snelling" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref22174" refString="Snelling R. R. 1984. Studies on the taxonomy and distribution of American Centridine bees (Hymenoptera: Anthophoridae). Contributions in Science, Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History 347: 1 - 69." type="journal article" year="1984">Snelling (1984)</bibRefCitation>
recognized the latter mistake and corrected the sex of the specimens. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Cockerell" box="[784,989,1152,1178]" firstAuthor="Cockerell" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="49 - 56" refId="ref19992" refString="Cockerell T. D. A. 1924. Anthophorid bees in the collection of the California Academy of Sciences. The Pan-Pacific Entomologist 1: 49 - 56." type="journal article" year="1924">Cockerell (1924)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Snelling" box="[1003,1188,1152,1178]" firstAuthor="Snelling" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref22174" refString="Snelling R. R. 1984. Studies on the taxonomy and distribution of American Centridine bees (Hymenoptera: Anthophoridae). Contributions in Science, Los Angeles County Museum of Natural History 347: 1 - 69." type="journal article" year="1984">Snelling (1984)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="Moure" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Moure" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" pagination="83 - 142" refId="ref21502" refString="Moure J. S., Melo G. A. R. &amp; Vivallo F. 2007. Centridini Cockerell &amp; Cockerell. In: Moure J. S., Urban D. &amp; Melo G. A. R. (orgs) Catalogue of Bees (Hymenoptera, Apoidea) in the Neotropical Region: 83 - 142. Sociedade Brasileira de Entomologia, Curitibrazil." type="book chapter" year="2007">
Moure 
<emphasis box="[1338,1399,1151,1177]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">et al.</emphasis>
(2007)
</bibRefCitation>
, the type specimens are housed at 
<collectionCode box="[686,746,1187,1213]" country="USA" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15690" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:34700" name="California Academy of Sciences" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="Museum">CAS</collectionCode>
, but actually they are in the 
<collectionCode box="[1088,1182,1187,1213]" country="USA" httpUri="http://grbio.org/cool/142r-0w94" name="Smithsonian Institution, National Museum of Natural History" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" type="Museum">NMNH</collectionCode>
. One of the males bears a label of “type” and the other was labeled as “cotype”. The 
<typeStatus box="[1014,1117,1221,1247]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">holotype</typeStatus>
has the following data label: [grey label] La Paz, Baja Calif., Mex. 
<date box="[709,873,1257,1283]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" value="1919-06-29">June 29, 1919</date>
G. F. Ferris. [printed]\ 
<taxonomicName authority="Ckll" authorityName="Cockerell" authorityYear="1924" class="Insecta" family="Apidae" genus="Centris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="30" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atripes" subSpecies="ferrisi">
<emphasis box="[1145,1399,1256,1283]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">Centris atripes ferrisi</emphasis>
Ckll
</taxonomicName>
Type [handwritten]\ California Academy of Sciences Type No. [printed] 2729 [handwritten]. The male 
